12.3  Atomic Spectra
As mentioned in Section 12.1, each element has a characteristic spectrum of radiation, which it emits.", "fibs": ["×"]}
{"text": "When an atomic gas or vapour is excited at low pressure, usually by passing an electric current through it, the emitted radiation has a spectrum which contains certain specific wavelengths only.", "fibs": ["gas"]}
{"text": "A spectrum of this kind is termed as emission line spectrum and it consists of bright lines on a dark background.", "fibs": ["spectrum"]}
{"text": "The spectrum emitted by atomic hydrogen is shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["spectrum"]}
{"text": "Study of emission line spectra of a material can therefore serve as a type of “fingerprint” for identification of the gas.", "fibs": ["emission"]}
{"text": "When white light passes through a gas and we analyse the transmitted light using a spectrometer we find some dark lines in the spectrum.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "These dark lines correspond precisely to those wavelengths which were found in the emission line spectrum of the gas.", "fibs": ["emission"]}
{"text": "This is called the absorption spectrum of the material of the gas.", "fibs": ["absorption"]}
{"text": "Figure 12.5 Emission lines in the spectrum of hydrogen.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "12.3.1  Spectral series
We might expect that the frequencies of the light emitted by a particular element would exhibit some regular pattern.", "fibs": ["series"]}
{"text": "Hydrogen is the simplest atom and therefore, has the simplest spectrum.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "In the observed spectrum, however, at first sight, there does not seem to be any resemblance of order or regularity in spectral lines.", "fibs": ["spectrum"]}
{"text": "But the spacing between lines within certain sets of the hydrogen spectrum decreases in a regular way (Fig.", "fibs": ["spacing"]}
{"text": "Each of these sets is called a spectral series.", "fibs": ["series"]}
{"text": "In 1885, the first such series was observed by a Swedish school teacher Johann Jakob Balmer (1825–1898) in the visible region of the hydrogen spectrum.", "fibs": ["series"]}
{"text": "This series is called Balmer series (Fig.", "fibs": ["series"]}
{"text": "The line with the longest wavelength, 656.3 nm in the red is called Hα; the next line with wavelength 486.1 nm in the blue-green is called Hβ, the third line 434.1 nm in the violet is called Hγ; and so on.", "fibs": ["line"]}
{"text": "As the wavelength decreases, the lines appear closer together and are weaker in intensity.", "fibs": ["wavelength"]}
