{"text": "12.4  Bohr Model of the Hydrogen Atom
The model of the atom proposed by Rutherford assumes that the atom, consisting of a central nucleus and revolving electron is stable much like sun-planet system which the model imitates.", "fibs": ["Model"]}
{"text": "While the planetary system is held by gravitational force, the nucleus-electron system being charged objects, interact by Coulomb’s Law of force.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "We know that an object which moves in a circle is being constantly accelerated – the acceleration being centripetal in nature.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "According to classical electromagnetic theory, an accelerating charged particle emits radiation in the form of electromagnetic waves.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "The energy of an accelerating electron should therefore, continuously decrease.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "The electron would spiral inward and eventually fall into the nucleus (Fig.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Thus, such an atom can not be stable.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "Further, according to the classical electromagnetic theory, the frequency of the electromagnetic waves emitted by the revolving electrons is equal to the frequency of revolution.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "As the electrons spiral inwards, their angular velocities and hence their frequencies would change continuously, and so will the frequency of the light emitted.", "fibs": ["spiral"]}
{"text": "Thus, they would emit a continuous spectrum, in contradiction to the line spectrum actually observed.", "fibs": ["spectrum"]}
{"text": "Clearly Rutherford model tells only a part of the story implying that the classical ideas are not sufficient to explain the atomic structure.", "fibs": ["model"]}
{"text": "Niels Henrik David Bohr (1885 – 1962)






Niels Henrik David Bohr (1885 – 1962) Danish physicist who explained the spectrum of hydrogen atom based on quantum ideas.", "fibs": ["physicist"]}
{"text": "He gave a theory of nuclear fission based on the liquid-drop model of nucleus.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "Bohr contributed to the clarification of conceptual problems in quantum mechanics, in particular by proposing the comple- mentary principle.", "fibs": ["clarification"]}
{"text": "Figure 12.7 An accelerated atomic electron must spiral into the nucleus as it loses energy.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "Example 12.4 According to the classical electromagnetic theory, calculate the initial frequency of the light emitted by the electron revolving around a proton in hydrogen atom.", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "Solution From Example 12.3 we know that velocity of electron moving around a proton in hydrogen atom in an orbit of radius 5.3 × 10–11 m is 2.2 × 10–6 m/s.", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "Thus, the frequency of the electron moving around the proton is

 ≈ 6.6 × 1015 Hz.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "According to the classical electromagnetic theory we know that the frequency of the electromagnetic waves emitted by the revolving electrons is equal to the frequency of its revolution around the nucleus.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "Thus the initial frequency of the light emitted is 6.6 × 1015 Hz.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "It was Niels Bohr (1885 – 1962) who made certain modifications in this model by adding the ideas of the newly developing quantum hypothesis.", "fibs": ["model"]}
{"text": "Niels Bohr studied in Rutherford’s laboratory for several months in 1912 and he was convinced about the validity of Rutherford nuclear model.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Faced with the dilemma as discussed above, Bohr, in 1913, concluded that in spite of the success of electromagnetic theory in explaining large-scale phenomena, it could not be applied to the processes at the atomic scale.", "fibs": ["dilemma"]}
{"text": "It became clear that a fairly radical departure from the established principles of classical mechanics and electromagnetism would be needed to understand the structure of atoms and the relation of atomic structure to atomic spectra.", "fibs": ["departure"]}
{"text": "Bohr combined classical and early quantum concepts and gave his theory in the form of three postulates.", "fibs": ["quantum"]}
{"text": "These are :
(i)	Bohr’s first postulate was that an electron in an atom could revolve in certain stable orbits without the emission of radiant energy, contrary to the predictions of electromagnetic theory.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "According to this postulate, each atom has certain definite stable states in which it can exist, and each possible state has definite total energy.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "These are called the stationary states of the atom.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "(ii)	Bohr’s second postulate defines these stable orbits.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "This postulate states that the electron revolves around the nucleus only in those orbits for which the angular momentum is some integral multiple of h/2π where h is the Planck’s constant (= 6.6 × 10–34 J s).", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Thus the angular momentum (L) of the orbiting electron is quantised.", "fibs": ["momentum"]}
{"text": "That is
	L = nh/2π            (12.11)
(iii)	Bohr’s third postulate incorporated into atomic theory the early quantum concepts that had been developed by Planck and Einstein.", "fibs": ["nh/2π"]}
{"text": "It states that an electron might make a transition from one of its specified non-radiating orbits to another of lower energy.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "When it does so, a photon is emitted having energy equal to the energy difference between the initial and final states.", "fibs": ["photon"]}
{"text": "The frequency of the emitted photon is then given by
 hν  =   Ei – Ef         (12.12)
where Ei and Ef are the energies of the initial and final states and Ei > Ef.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "For a hydrogen atom, Eq.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "(12.4) gives the expression to determine the energies of different energy states.", "fibs": ["expression"]}
{"text": "But then this equation requires the radius r of the electron orbit.", "fibs": ["equation"]}
{"text": "To calculate r, Bohr’s second postulate about the angular momentum of the electron–the quantisation condition – is used.", "fibs": ["r"]}
{"text": "The angular momentum L is given by
L = mvr
