{"text": "Orbit vs state (orbital picture) of electron in atom
We are introduced to the Bohr Model of atom one time or the other in the course of physics.", "fibs": ["Orbit"]}
{"text": "This model has its place in the history of quantum mechanics and particularly in explaining the structure of an atom.", "fibs": ["model"]}
{"text": "It has become a milestone since Bohr introduced the revolutionary idea of definite energy orbits for the electrons, contrary to the classical picture requiring an accelerating particle to radiate.", "fibs": ["milestone"]}
{"text": "Bohr also introduced the idea of quantisation of angular momentum of electrons moving in definite orbits.", "fibs": ["idea"]}
{"text": "Thus it was a semi-classical picture of the structure of atom.", "fibs": ["picture"]}
{"text": "Now with the development of quantum mechanics, we have a better understanding of the structure of atom.", "fibs": ["development"]}
{"text": "Solutions of the Schrödinger wave equation assign a wave-like description to the electrons bound in an atom due to attractive forces of the protons.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "An orbit of the electron in the Bohr model is the circular path of motion of an electron around the nucleus.", "fibs": ["orbit"]}
{"text": "But according to quantum mechanics, we cannot associate a definite path with the motion of the electrons in an atom.", "fibs": ["quantum"]}
{"text": "We can only talk about the probability of finding an electron in a certain region of space around the nucleus.", "fibs": ["probability"]}
{"text": "This probability can be inferred from the one-electron wave function called the orbital.", "fibs": ["probability"]}
{"text": "This function depends only on the coordinates of the electron.", "fibs": ["function"]}
{"text": "It is therefore essential that we understand the subtle differences that exist in the two models:
- Bohr model is valid for only one-electron atoms/ions; an energy value, assigned to each orbit, depends on the principal quantum number n in this model.", "fibs": ["model"]}
{"text": "We know that energy associated with a stationary state of an electron depends on n only, for one-electron atoms/ions.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "For a multi-electron atom/ion, this is not true.", "fibs": ["atom/ion"]}
{"text": "- The solution of the Schrödinger wave equation, obtained for hydrogen-like atoms/ions, called the wave function, gives information about the probability of finding an electron in various regions around the nucleus.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "This orbital has no resemblance whatsoever with the orbit defined for an electron in the Bohr model.", "fibs": ["resemblance"]}
