{"text": "12.4.1  Energy levels
The energy of an atom is the least (largest negative value) when its electron is revolving in an orbit closest to the nucleus i.e., the one for which n = 1.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "For n = 2, 3, ... the absolute value of the energy E is smaller, hence the energy is progressively larger in the outer orbits.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "The lowest state of the atom, called the ground state, is that of the lowest energy, with the electron revolving in the orbit of smallest radius, the Bohr radius, a0.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "The energy of this state (n = 1), E1 is –13.6 eV.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Therefore, the minimum energy required to free the electron from the ground state of the hydrogen atom is 13.6 eV.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "It is called the ionisation energy of the hydrogen atom.", "fibs": ["ionisation"]}
{"text": "This prediction of the Bohr’s model is in excellent agreement with the experimental value of ionisation energy.", "fibs": ["prediction"]}
